{
  "doc_id": "2485",
  "text": "In the past decade, it has become clear that chronic diseases often coexist [CITATION_1] . Accordingly, COPD patients often suffer from other chronic diseases (called comorbidities). Cardiovascular diseases, psychological disorders (e.g., anxiety and/or depression), metabolic disorders (e.g., diabetes, dyslipidemia, and metabolic syndrome), and cancer have been found highly prevalent among COPD patients [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The association of comorbidities and COPD may merely reflect common risk factors (e.g., age or cigarette smoking). However, chronic low-grade systemic inflammation, which is observed in some COPD patients, could also be involved [CITATION_4] , as well as biological mechanisms related to decreased physical activity, which is often observed with ageing [CITATION_5] . The importance of coexisting diseases has been underscored by several studies showing that COPD patients with multiple comorbidities have worse prognosis [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . However, it has not been established whether the presence of one or several of these comorbidities represent or contribute to a coherent phenotype per se.",
